Using confidence intervals for testing hypotheses


Getting started

Goal

Use confidence intervals to test for statistical significance.



The data story

Who has big brains? Its not an easy thing to measure! Willeman et al.conducted a study that used magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) to measure brain size. The MRI scans consisted of 18 horizontal MR images that were 5 mm thick and 2.5 mm apart. Further, each image covered a 256 x 256 pixel area. Any pixel with a non-zero gray scale was considered to be part of the brain.

image source

Using data on 38 subjects, well explore the association between brain size and height:

Variable Description
MRICount total pixel count of non-zero gray scale in 18 MRI scans (the larger the count, the larger the brain!)
Height subjects height in inches


The actual relationship between these quantitative variables in the population of all adults can be represented by the equation

\[\text{MRICount} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \text{Height}\]

where \(\beta_0\) and \(\beta_1\) are unknown. Instead, well estimate this model using our sample data:

# Load packages
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Import data
brain <- read.csv("https://www.macalester.edu/~ajohns24/data/BrainEESEE.csv")

# Construct the sample model
brain_mod_1 <- lm(MRICount ~ Height, data = brain)
summary(brain_mod_1)$coefficients
##              Estimate Std. Error  t value     Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 175331.96 167805.714 1.044851 0.3030573100
## Height       10690.02   2448.487 4.365968 0.0001022773
# Plot the model
ggplot(brain, aes(x = Height, y = MRICount)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)





Exercises

Exercise 1: REVIEW: CI for slope \(\beta_1\)

  1. Use the CLT with the 68-95-99.7 Rule to calculate an approximate 95% CI for the true \(\beta_1\). Check your work:
confint(brain_mod_1, level = 0.95)
##                   2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) -164993.801 515657.72
## Height         5724.255  15655.78
  1. How can we interpret this CI?
    • Were 95% confident that for every 1 inch increase in height, the corresponding (average) increase in brain size for people in the population is between 5724.255 and 15655.78 pixels.



Exercise 2: Inference for \(\beta_1\)

  1. What can we conclude from the 95% CI for \(\beta_1\): is there significant evidence of a positive association between height and brain size? Explain your reasoning.

Yes, the lower confint bound is still very positive.

  1. Alternatively (yet equivalently), answer this question using the confidence bands around our sample model trend. NOTE: These confidence bands are reminiscent of our sampling distribution simulations which produced a range of model trends.
ggplot(brain, aes(x = Height, y = MRICount)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The smallest slope is still positive.



Exercise 3: Statistical vs meaningful significance

Above, you shouldve concluded that theres a statistically significant relationship between brain size and height. Based on the plot of the data, does it appear that the magnitude of this relationship is also meaningfully significant?

We dont have enough context to talk about meaningful significance.



Exercise 4: Model prediction

Consider using the sample model to predict brain size by height. There are 2 types of predictions we can make for, say, a height of 72 inches (6 feet):

  • Predict the average brain size of all people that are 72 inches tall.
  • Predict the brain size of Jo, a specific person thats 72 inches tall.

The values of the two predictions are the same:

MRICount = 175332 + 10690*72 = 945012 pixels

However, the potential error in these predictions differs. Check in with your intuition: Is there more error in trying to predict the average brain size of all people that are 72 inches tall, or the brain size of Jo, a particular person thats 72 inches tall? Explain your reasoning.

Its more possible that Jos brain is an outlier than the average person, so theirs has the biggest average brain size error.

Exercise 5: Confidence intervals & confidence bands

  1. Check your intuition. Calculate and report the 95% confidence interval for the average brain size of all people that are 72 inches tall:
predict(brain_mod_1, newdata = data.frame(Height = 72),
  interval = "confidence", level = 0.95)
##        fit    lwr      upr
## 1 945013.2 918578 971448.3
NOTE: `fit` is the prediction (which due to rounding is slightly different than our "by hand" prediction), `lwr` gives the lower bound of the CI, and `upr` gives the upper bound of the CI.
  1. Whats the best interpretation of this interval?
    • Among all 72 inch tall people in the population, were 95% confident that the mean brain size is in this interval.
  2. We can visualize the confidence interval for the average brain size of all people at any common Height (not just 72 inches) by drawing confidence bands around the model. The vertical line drawn at a Height of 72 inches reflects the interval you calculated above. NOTE: What have we changed in the syntax?
ggplot(brain, aes(x = Height, y = MRICount)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  geom_segment(aes(x = 72, xend = 72, y = 918578, yend = 971448.3))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'



Exercise 6: Prediction intervals

  1. Calculate and report the 95% prediction interval (PI) for the brain size of Jo, a specific person thats 72 inches tall. NOTE: What changed in the syntax?
predict(brain_mod_1, newdata = data.frame(Height = 72),
  interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
##        fit      lwr     upr
## 1 945013.2 821516.1 1068510
  1. How can we interpret this interval?
    • Among all 72 inch tall people in the population, were 95% confident that the mean brain size is in this interval.



Exercise 7: Prediction vs confidence bands

We can visualize the prediction interval for the brain size of a person at any Height by drawing prediction bands. This requires some messy syntax:

# Calculate and store prediction intervals for every Height value
pred_int_1 <- data.frame(brain, predict(brain_mod_1, 
  newdata = data.frame(Height = brain$Height), 
  interval = 'prediction'))

head(pred_int_1)
##   FSIQ VIQ PIQ Weight Height MRICount      fit      lwr       upr
## 1  133 132 124    118   64.5   816932 864838.1 741085.1  988591.0
## 2  139 123 150    143   73.3  1038437 958910.2 834320.3 1083500.2
## 3  133 129 128    172   68.8   965353 910805.1 788579.0 1033031.2
## 4  137 132 134    147   65.0   951545 870183.1 746796.4  993569.8
## 5   99  90 110    146   69.0   928799 912943.1 790697.7 1035188.6
## 6  138 136 131    138   64.5   991305 864838.1 741085.1  988591.0
# Plot regression line with prediction bands
ggplot(pred_int_1, aes(x = Height, y = MRICount)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color = "black") + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(y = fit, ymin = lwr, ymax = upr, fill = 'prediction'), alpha = 0.2)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  1. Do the confidence bands (gray) capture the uncertainty of the AVERAGE TREND or the uncertainty of the INDIVIDUAL BEHAVIOR?

The average trend.

  1. Do the prediction bands (pink) capture the uncertainty of the AVERAGE TREND or the uncertainty of the INDIVIDUAL BEHAVIOR?

Individual behavior.

  1. Which are wider, intervals for the average brain size of all people of a common height OR the interval for the brain size of a specific person at that height? Explain why this makes intuitive sense.

Specific people, because those are the dots with the large deviation from the trend line.



Exercise 8: Narrowing

Though its not as noticeable with the prediction bands, these and the confidence bands are always the most narrow at the same point in this case at a height of 68.42105 inches. What other meaning does this value have? Provide some proof and explain why it makes intuitive sense that the bands are narrowest at this point.

This is likely the average height, or the place where there is the highest density of samples. This would cause every metric to narrow because there is more data at this point.

    • Thus how can we interpret the t value for the VIQ coefficient? HINT: Subtract 0 in the numerator of your calculation (which doesnt do anything mathematically, but helps with interpretation).
  • Check out the number in the Pr(>|t|) column for the VIQ coefficient: 0.06699. This is a probability. Whats it the probability of? HINT: This plays off of the t value.
